column76: The ARU used was an LG phone running Arbimon software. Recordings made using these devices resulted in faint sonograms, and pattern matching algorithms do not work well. Manual analysis of the recordings allowed for detection of vocalizations. This site was part of my first paper. When initially analyzed I noted some young birds in May when manually reviewing the site. Later Pattern Matching analysis did not match my manual analysis, so I have revisited all of these calls, and unfortunately my earlier analysis included errors in my assignment to hatchling and nestling as there was another non-trbl nestling that confused me. I have reviewed all of these calls and have corrected them. There are a handful of TRBL Hatchling and Fledgling calls May 1-3, but then they stop. So, there were either only a handful of nests that hatched any young. Thus, the first attempt in April/May was largely not even attempted. The few hatchlings that are heard are so few that I am unable to determine if they successfully fledged, or if they were abandoned. Susequently, there was a replacement pulse with the first bout in in May and the second bout in June, both of which successfully at producing fledglings. Unfortunately for the first bout there are a few days that coincide with hatching where the recording are unusable. The hatchling dates listed here in late May are potentially a day or two earlier than stated. Note this site had intense manual analysis as it was initially analyzed before pattern matching was available.

column81: Site is an approx. 4500 sq. meter (1.2 acre) stock pond within a ~400 acre grassland matrix that also hosts CA red-legged frog, CA tiger salamander, and seasonal waterfowl. Surrounding land uses are ranching and horse boarding. There is a shooting range nearby (you may hear shots). I noted about 100 TCBL at the pond April 12. Unfortunately when I returned to place the recorder, they appear to have been supplanted by RWBL. I observed one male TCBL that was chased off the pond by a male RWBL a few times.  I hope the TCBL return!
column85: Amy Richey, Preserve Manager, Center for Natural Lands Management
column86: AudioMoth "H", 2 weeks prior to placement of the recorder the site had a lot of TRBLs (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy "4/14/2021: "On 4/12/2021 I observed nesting behavior at one of our CNLM preserves in Alameda County.  There were about 100 birds; some of them were carrying nesting material in their beaks". Only one TRBL seen at time of deployment (audio recording 4/29/2021 10:28). Email from Amy 7/14/2021: "I'm afraid this site probably didn't pan out for our TRBL after all, sadly.  When I deployed, there were over 100 trikes, but by the second visit they had decamped and only a dozen remained, then finally only one lonely male who was getting chased off the marsh by RWBBs."

column76: This site was so asynchronous that I did a manual analysis for many days. These tags, "reviewed-WS-e", will not show up in the automatically generated reports. The first pulse can been seen as asynchrounous since hatching day for the colony was 12-May and last female song was 19-May. There is also evidence of a second pulse, though no YNC are picked up. But if there were YNC I doubt that they could have been picked up due to the loud pulse 1 nestlings which would have been present. Based on Hatch day, pulse 1 should have dispersed around June 3-8. I see the majority of the fledglings leave 5-Jun, and another drop on 10-Jun. If the 2nd pulse had been productive, it was also highly asynchronous and female song was heard all the way through to the end of the recordings. I estimate that the second pulse would have started hatching ~ 6/3 and then would have fledged 6/28, and with the extended Female Song that hatching would have been still on going. This would account for the long tail of nestlings.

column76: Manually analyzed data. Large Ibis colony very loud. Recorder appears to be a little distant to where the TRBLs are, but I can her the vocalizations. Many are too faint for template analysis, so a mini manual, followed by edge analysis was performed. Recorder was placed after settlement. Somewhere around when they fail you can hear what I believe might be the other part of the colony right as they are about to fledge. I also think I hear a lot of EUST around this time. There were lots of nestlings up until about 7/6-7/7. Then there is just one or two that hang on. I am calling it a failure at the 7/7ish date. Interestingly this is the date that the other two colonies fledged. My take is that this area was a late attempt compared to the other two areas. And that the majority of the nestlings were old enough to join the crowd when the rest of the colony left the area. Template worked marginally for MS and NC and did not work at all for FS.FS couldn't be located using template analysis. Did mark presence of Female Song when reviewing recordings, so last date here is from these manually reviewed recordings. Recorder was placed just before hatching date, so no Male Chorus. Manual analysis.

column76: This data set needs a complete relook now that I have my head wrapped around subcolony additions, constant nesting, etc. Look at all of the graphs and really rethink what makes up a pulse. Asynchronous colony that had hints of pulses. Tried my best to document the rough dates of these pulses. Since the colony is aysnchronous these are very rough. After initial Male chorus, there is a scattering of male chorus later in the season, these are marked in the mini-manual analysis and I marked p2c and p3c as best I could to capture these. These other pulses are not as sustained as the first, and female song continues throughout this time. So while there may be other pulses within this colony, but they are not clearly definged. Nestling heard at the end, I think it is not a TRBL, I tagged them as "other nestling" and validated as TRBL nestling call not present. This other nestling has a doublet calls, and it seems less fuzzy and more compact than the TRBL nestling call. Might need to review these all again more carefully. I attempted to mark the 3 pulses even though the dates are a bit blurry due to overlapping pulses and lack of synchrony. The first pulse is smaller than the second, and the fledgling chorus is barely mutliple ONC, but I think I have it right. For feldgling/simple call 2 I am marking the dates with the louder full kHtz calls. UPDATE: By adding the Fledgling Call I think I have this teased out well. I expanded the MC, and can see the three bouts. The 2nd bout of Fledglings is quite brief, existing for really only 5/30. Brian noted colony size in email on Aug 23, 2022.

column76: Recorder either ran out of battery or was pulled before nestlings fledged. Colony was too small to generate a male chorus, so incubation onset will need to be estimated at 11 days before hatch day. Unkown if nestlings survived to fledging as recordings stopped when they were only ~8 days old. There is a hint that there may have been an earlier attempt. I have one recording with YNC on 5/16/2022 and there is also a weak FS bout that correlates with this as well as a couple of FCs that imply a fledging date od 5/30. So I am betting that there was actually pulse 1 with hatch day before 5/16 and that these young fledged somewhere around/before 5/30. And there is a second round hatching around 5/27 and these would have fledged after the recordngs stopped. If this is the case, then this suggests a sub colony addition. Unfortunately the recordings re so faint that I cannot be sure.

There is a long tail of nestings heard, also these older nestlings are hard to be certain that they are really TRBL and not another nestling like BWBL. column76: Something about these vocalizations sounds different to me, suggesting that in addition to the MS sounding different in this population, so does the Nestling calls. Note 4/21/2022 1600 there is a human laugh recorded. One recorder has it at 17 sec and the other at 27 sec, so if these are in sync at all, the two recorders are approximately 10X343m apart, or 3,430 meters apart, soooo.... I think that says they aren't in sync. Debi reports that the recorders ar ~100m apart. So, good news recorders agree with date/time/min. Bad news for triangulation they are not in sync at the seconds level. Fledgling dispersal was calculated by scanning thumbnails for a drop in consistent nestling chorus. This was later documented with p1f tag.

column76: Female song continued for more than 20 days after first nestling heard, so this is a very asynchrounous colony. Also hear young nestlings scattered throughout suggesting the lack of synchrony when hatching. There also was no clear cessation of male chorus. Because of this I did not document male chorus. While nestling calls can be heard through 6/1/2022, there is a large drop in density of Nestlng calls starting the 5/26, so I have marked this as the dispersal date for the colony. Tagged one of the last dense recordings with the tag "p1 dispersal". Likely most of the stragglers were abandoned as the YNCs do not continue past 6/1, and they sounded to young the have fledged. But this is pure speculation. IMPORTANT NOTE - I need to obsfucate the location as this was placed on a dairy farm field with equirement that exact location is not published.

column76: The colony had two distinct and non-overlapping bouts of breeding, both of which successfully fledged young (Figure 3B). The ARU was placed after the initiation of prospecting, so the date of onset of this breeding phase could not be determined.  Dates for all other breeding phases could be estimated from the recordings (Table 3). Due to the greater abundance of vocalizations in the first bout, this bout was likely a larger effort that resulted in more fledglings.

column86: I deployed the ARU this year, and observed about 600 birds which came into the marsh in the evening and departed early the next morning, presumably to feed.

column76: Male Chorus was likely missed. There is a constant blur of the colony and other birds of the area that extends all the way past hatch date that I would consider just the background of an occupied colony or sounds of the additional species occupying the marsh. I believe that the increased male chorus was missed and occurred before the recorder was placed. It could also be that the male chorus is indistinguisable from the background of the marsh. It is also possible that the colony was not synchrouous and there was no real end to male chorus. Nestling/Fledgling heard through end of recordings, but drop in calls suggests 6/23/2022 as the dispersal day for the majority of the nestlings.

column76: Sub-colony addition. After the first birds established a larger group appears to have joined them, resulting in overlapping breeding stages.  Based on density of nestling calls the second addition of birds was significanly larger than the first. The hatching date for the colony for pulse 1 is estimated, as the onset of pulse 2 Male Chorus drowns out the nestlings. So dates marked as nestling call not present when there is the loud male chorus are likely just because I can't hear them. When I do finally hear them, it is obvious that they are older nestlings. A few nestlings were heard on 5/17, and with most colonies the majority of hatching happens the day after first nestlings are heard, so I estimate that hatching date is ~5/18. The Fledgling dispersal date of pulse 1 is also an estimate as the calls from pulse 2 nestlings make it hard to determine the exact date. For recordings that were analyzed to determine the edge of hatching and dispersal (p1n, p2n) where the two pulaes overlapped I have marked the YNC with the tag YNC-p2 and the older nestling calls with ONC-p1 to distinguish between the two pulses of nestlings. I picked the p1 dispersal date on the day that seemed to have a lull in the ONC. There is a temporary lull in p2 nestling calls 6/12-6/13. There was also a rain storm on that day which maybe explains the lull. The majority of the nestlings disperse on 7/3/2022 (last day with high volume of NCs), but stragglers can be heard thru the end of the recordings. Battery started running out on July 4th and completely died by July 13th.

column76: The recorder didn't pick up the colony very well and all vocalizations are quite faint. FS is never heard, but there is almost continuous chorus, and I can hear the young. I am betting that the young hatch multiple days before I pick them up on the recording. Analysis of the Fledgling Calls suggests there were two successful pulses, with the first pulse starting with a small group and then a larger sub-colony addition. This lead to a Fledling call from 5/1-5/6, 5/22-6/5, and 6/21-6/24. I can estimate the breeding stages as Pulse #1: There was a pulse that started incubating ~4/6, hatched ~4/16, and confirmed to have fledged on 5/1 - and these fledglings hung around for about until 5/6, so hung out for a total of 6 days. Since the recorder was placed on 4/14 I am unable to document the onset of incubation. Hatchlings are too far away to hear until they get a few days old. First nestlings are heard on  There was a sub-colony addition to this first pulse, with this addition starting incubation ~4/28, hatching ~5/8, and was confirmed to have fledged on 5/22 and these fledglings hung around until 6/5, or 15 days. When marking MC - looked for SOLID bands just above and below 2kHz, because of the distance of the chorusing at times, it looks underwhelming compared to other recordings which have Male Song at a closer distance, but they were not a SOLID band. Pulse #2: Once this first pulse was completed, a Replacement Pulse was initiated and incubation began ~5/27, hatching ~6/7, and this pulse fledged on 6/21 and stuck around until 6/24 for a total of 4 days, when the majority of the fledgling calls cease. There is a long tail of occasional fledgling calls that extends through 7/27. I do not know if these are stragglers finishing up a really late breeding attempt, or if these are just fledglings that are re-visiting the area occasionally. Mini Manual was completed.

column76: It appears that a few fledglings from T27.1 are heard here in T27.1 just after they fledged, confusing analysis. These older birds are not the end of an earlier pulse in T27.1 because there is no evidence of Female Chatter, YNC, or MNC at all in the recordings evn though the recorder was placed with sufficient time to capture these vocalizations if they had been there. Therefore, I am only documenting a single pulse at this location, though because the ON from the other location are around, I need to document this as p2 to tease the two sets of nestlings apart. Additionally, there may be straggler p1 nestlings in the recordings as well, as they don't quite sound like fledglings to me in all of the recordings where I hear ONC when I "shouldn't". Interestingly, I believe that the birds from T27.2 have shifted their second attempt to T27.1 rather than do a replacement pulse in T27.2 and reusing previous nesting areas, thus the marking as p2 would be appropriate. The number of breeding birds is tiny in this pulse. By the end there are just a few straggling nestlings that can be heard to the end of the recordings. I did manage to document at least one fledgling on 7/27/2023 making the Fledgling calls, and I marked these as Simple Call 2 Present. Many of these calls are starting to take on the Flight-call "yip" sound, but their sonograms are much fuzzier and haven't quite developed the crisp sonogram that the adults have. For making summary excel this "second" pulse has been placed in the "first pulse" slot.

column76: This was a small asynchronous colony. I suspect that in small colonies we hear "younger" calls for longer. Maybe becausethey don't have as much competition so can be quieter? I struggled with if I should mark a p2n. There are some really young nestlngs heard on 5/14 that I initially thought were from a second pulse. Upon more careful examiniation I believe that this was an asynchrounous colony and the bulk of the nestlings have fledged and disperse by 5/17. Since I hear some FS all the way through 5/2 I suspect that I am just hearing the "dribbles" from the lat nesters. Female Song never took a break and the stated up again, so doesn't act like 2 pulses. It was a continuous decline from hatch day through 5/2. If these young birds that I hear on 5/14 are from the FS 5/2 it would make them only a couple of days old.

column76: This was a highly asynchronous colony. Based on what I hear I believe this was one with a continual expansion/egg laying in each pulse rather than a sub-colony addition. The asynchrony made it challenging to determine MC for pulse 2 asn well as HD for pulse 2. For MC2 I looked for signs of MS at just above Khz 2, and have put a p2c tag at where this band is for many of the recordings. For HD2 I relyed on PMJs to locate recordings with signals of very young nestlings. I then focused on these dates and zoomed in so 8-0 Ktz and about 4 sec were showing on the sonogram. I then looked visually for the signature of very young nestings. It was too hard to try and use my ears to decide if it was a very young nestling or a late nesting from pulse 1.

column76:
The ARU was placed after the onset of settlement. Male chorus continued until the first hatchlings were heard, and female chatter was heard for 13 days after the first hatchlings were heard, suggesting a continuous breeding form (Figure 3C, Table 3). The colony had a single bout of breeding that successfully produced young.
In addition to monitoring the colony through audio recordings, volunteers conducted several in-person visits (Table XX). In general, observations made during the visits aligned with the interpretation of breeding stages through analysis of the audio. Of note, volunteers saw fledglings dispersing on the same date that a large drop in fledgling calls was identified in the audio analysis, helping to confirm that the sharp drop in fledgling calls can be used to estimate dates of creche dispersal.
column77: This was highly asynchronous. The bulk of the nestlings hatch ~4/20ish. I suspect that this is a continuously nesting colony. Because of this I did a manual analysis. Also for MC, I just did three recordings/day every third day. I tagged a scattering of very young nestlings with YNC and older with MNC to show the lack of asynchrony. There might have been something that happened to the recording quality around May 14th in that recordings appear blank. But occassionally I get a recording with something in it, so it could just be a quiet site. UPDATE I went and filled in MC by examining every day from start to end of the first bout. It continues until 4/17. This happens to be 11 days before the last Female Chatter, so I think that there was continuous nesting initiation from until 4/17. Incubation would have been starting from 4/5 and continuously was initiation until 4/17.

column76: There were a few recordings with Male Song, and then at the end of the season a fledgling calls can be heard. Because Pattern Matching did'nt work well a mini-manual analysis was performed, and it also failed to detect Female Chatter and nestling calls. Jason reports that there was a colony of ~100 birds at this location and has an account of food carrying on 5/29. I suspect that for some reason the recorder did not pick up the colony very well, and it only registered the louder vocalizations of the Male Song and Fledgling calls, much like Baja this year. I also suspect that the lack of Male Chorus is just due to the small number of birds. Unfortunately, the lack of robust vocalizations make it so I can't tell much from this site. Based on Fledgling call alone a super tentative guess would be Fledging day of 6/17, whch would put hatch day at ~6/3, and incubation start at ~5/23. But this doesn't agree with ebird reports or field visits. Though it is just a few days off. If Food carries on 3/29 (in-person) was the date of hatching, and if on the longer end for fledgling (14days) then date of fledging would be 6/12. Also, with feeding of Fladglings still seen on Aug, this could have been a continuous nesting site. If this was a continuous nesting site, with the small number of birds I would have had an even lower number of vcalizations to pick up, and this might be beyond the reach of my analysis detection abilities. Also of note, this site was much later than the McCain Wetlands and timing suggests that this could be the same birds as at McCain Wetlands but their second bout of breeding.

Rain on day during hatching. I was never satisfied with the templates and the number of vocalizations validated. Since this is a continuous site, there is a mixture of vocalizations, and thus any particular signal get diluted from the other vocalizations that are present. I have confirmed that the nestling and fledgling calls at the very end are correct. The bulk of the breeding occured during May, but there was an extremely long tail, and the slightest hint that there may have been 2 additional replacement pulses. This can be seen with the two additional blocks of nestling calls, the onset of each one about 30 days after the onset of the preceding pulse, which suggests replacement pulses.

column76:
The ARU was placed during the settlement phase. Male chorus continued until a few days after the first hatchlings were heard, and female chatter was heard weeks after the first hatchlings were detected, both of which indicate a continuous breeding pattern. The presence of nestling followed by fledgling begging calls was detected from mid-April continuously through mid-June. The presence of fledgling calls indicate this colony was successful.

Female chatter was not fully documented, as I confidently identified only 27 vocalizations of this kind throughout the season, instead of a hundred or more that are typically noted. While 2023 followed a similar breeding pattern, I was able to detect more female chatter in that year. One notable difference is that in 2023, male chorus ended right as hatchlings were first detected, whereas in 2024, male chorus extended well past the detection of the first hatchlings. Thus, in 2024, there was no period lacking male chorus or loud nestling calls, both of which can drown out the softer female chatter.
